Somewhat rare hard-to-find. 90% Swiss made 556. Has fish gill model handguard and M4 style lower Swiss parts. title: For Sale/Trade:  Leupold VX-6 Firedot CDS 2-12x42mm
location: Clayton, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
I have a brand new, still sealed in the box, Leupold model 111979 VX-6 2-12x42mm scope with the Firedot Duplex reticle and the (CDS) custom dial system.  This is a 30mm tube scope that has 70 MOA of internal adjustment and comes with elevation and windage adjustment dials marked in true ¼ MOA, not ¼” @ 100 yard adjustments. Leupold will give you one free customized dial when you contact them with your specific rifle cartridge information. They'll send you a custom made elevation turret dial that is marked in yardage that will allow you to very accurately dial in for bullet drop compensation of your specific bullet trajectory drop.  This is a much more accurate method than using BDC style reticles and has a much less cluttered \ confusing view through the scope as well.  BDC reticles are built using an averaging method of various rifle bullet velocities and ballistic coefficients so they may get you close to target out at range but are far from ideal to really depend on for bullet drop corrections. I have played with these VX-6 scopes enough to fully trust their adjustments. I have all my VX-6 scoped rifles zeroed in at 100 yards and have played with them out to 530 yards so far and every time the adjustments are right on at various ranges out to 530 yards. They all return my point of impact back to 100 yards when dialing the turret back to its zero mark. 530 yards just happens to be the max distance I have available to me to shoot but I sure wish I had access to a longer range.   More dials can be ordered through Leupold for this scope at any time in case you wanted to use different loadings for your rifle later on or even use the scope on a totally different rifle and caliber.  The Firedot on these scopes is awesome in low light or during day time use. When the scope is set to 2X magnification it can be used as a red dot optic for quick target acquisition. On 2X it has enough field of view I can see the last couple inches of my 22” rifle barrel that it’s mounted on.  I have a 1-6x24mm VX-6 mounted on a 16” AR and I can see the whole flash suppressor when it’s set on 1X.
I bought my first VX-6 Firedot a year ago and liked it so much I ended up buying 4 more recently to re-scope all my rifles with but after thinking about it I've decided to not re-scope one of my rifles that I rarely shoot so I'm offering this brand new scope up for sell at a discount to someone wanting a top end optic for their favorite hunting, target or AR rifle.  Look around, check prices and reviews of these scopes and you'll see this is a very fair deal for this top end optic.
I have been swamped with trade offers for this scope so unless you have SPECIFICALLY one of the firearms that I've listed below as being interested in then don’t make trade offers. If you still feel so inclined to make a trade offer with something other than what’s listed then be willing to part with your item at a bargain price and include what that price is so I can consider; otherwise I will not waist time with responding. Thanks

title: For Sale:  180gr Swift Scirocco 30-06
location: Clayton, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent: I have 9 new boxes of 180gr Swift Scirocco 30-06 ammo for sell at $30 per box.  If you know anything about these Swift Scirocco bullets then you know they are a top quality bullet for taking thicker skinned game at long distances.  They have great external ballistic performance for long range shooting like long range target bullets do but they have a bonded jacket to keep the bullet intact on impact for desirable terminal ballistics on hunted game. These rounds will certainly work on our local whitetale deer but there certainly isn't a need to use such a premium round on our smaller whitetales in this area.  These rounds would be ideal for someone planning to take an elk or mule deer hunt out west, especially for longer range shots.  They would probably be great for black bear or hogs here or great for some larger northern whitetales.

title: For Sale:  H&R Pardner Shotgun (12 ga) + accessories
location: Smithfield, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent: For sale is a well used American made H&R Pardner single-shot break-open shotgun. I bought this shotgun (my first gun) new in July of 2014 for $189. Due to a change in careers I am selling off my gun collection, and this gun is the last to go.The barrel is 18.5 inches long, cylinder bore, no bead sight (though there is an untapped hole for a sight). The bluing is in good condition. The barrel was sawed off shortly after purchase; the cut end has been filed and heat-blued and is not warped or cut crookedly. The barrel securement is tight, though not overly so; if the release lever is depressed, a flick of the arm will cause the barrel to break downward. Closing it with two hands is recommended. There is no looseness when the gun is broken open, and the manufacturer describes the lockup as "tight as a bank vault door". After thousands of rounds, this still holds true. The single-action hammer must be cocked before each shot. A transfer bar prevents a discharge if the trigger is not pulled. The trigger cleanly breaks at 9 ounces. The firing pin hits hard; I have never had a misfire with this gun when using modern shotgun ammunition. An ejector will throw the spent shell a few feet back over the shooter's shoulder when the barrel is opened. Some brands of ammunition don't eject as well as others; I have never had a problem with Federal or Remington ammo, but Winchester White Box or Suprema 00 buckshot sometimes refuses to eject. If the chamber is clean and lubricated, all shells should eject properly.The stock has a couple holes drilled in it, and it is chipped near the butt. The length of pull is around 13 inches, good for all sizes. The forend is wood. A small hole has been drilled in it for a sling lug. There are a few scratches in it. Otherwise it is unchanged.Recoil: Recoil is manageable by anyone when using light birdshot rounds. The buttstock is equipped with an aftermarket recoil pad not fitted for the gun, but it works. Shooting 3'' loads out of this five pound gun is not for the first time shooter, however. The pad prevents bruising, but the kick is still fierce.Spread: Rule of thumb, one inch of spread for every yard of distance. The type of ammo you choose will affect the spread significantly. With clay pigeons, if you aim right, this shotgun can hit it. I am including a few other accessories: A 3 inch unrifled steel adapter that allows this shotgun to shoot 9mm Luger rounds. It is reasonably accurate with some practice, 3 inch groups at 25 yards without a rest. The entire adapter will eject when the shotgun is opened. A buttstock sleeve that holds five rounds. An ammo belt that holds 25 rounds. An assorted bag of ammunition, containing a few rounds of 00 buck, #4 buck, 1 oz rifled slugs, 7/8 oz high velocity slugs, rubber bullets, 1 3/8 oz Brenneke slugs, and a few brass 9mm. Total is about 30 rounds.The factory lock for the gun.Drop a line if you are interested.
